<HEADLINE>
<P>
FUROR OVER BIBLE SCHOLARS ON SECOND COMING OF CHRIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Jesus Seminar scholars are fulfilling Bible prophecy they decry when they 
proclaim that Jesus did not say He would return. The Bible says, " . . . In the 
last days mockers will come with their mocking . . . saying, 'Where is the 
promise of His coming?' For ever since the fathers fell asleep, all continues 
just as it was from the beginning of creation" (II Peter 3:3,4). 
</P>
<P>
The scoffers of the academe must establish their biblical credibility by 
explaining who Jesus was. In John 14:28, Jesus said to his disciples and to the 
multitudes who would believe in him throughout the ages, "I said unto you, I go 
away, and come again unto you." If he does not return, then he is a liar and 
the entire Christian faith is based upon a falsehood. The truth of the second 
coming dominates the New Testament; it is mentioned 318 times, more often than 
any other fundamental doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
These academicians may be wise in other subjects, but they should not be called 
biblical scholars, since they would have to cut out a major portion of their 
Bibles. They would not be left with a shred of evidence for their premise. We 
are grateful to Beutner for warning us that most major universities and 
seminaries agree with the findings. It should urge open-minded people to search 
the Scriptures for themselves -- before it is too late. 
</P>
<P>
CAROLE C. CARLSON 
</P>
<P>
Solvang 
</P>
</TEXT>
