<HEADLINE>
<P>
MANAGUA FREES 1,894 SOMOZA GUARD VETERANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICHARD BOUDREAUX, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TIPITAPA, Nicaragua 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nearly 10 years after their army collapsed in defeat in the Sandinista 
revolution, 1,645 former national guardsmen walked out of a prison Friday in a 
mass pardon aimed at ending the U.S.-backed rebellion against Sandinista rule. 
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony resembling a high school commencement, the prisoners stood in 
formation on a hot, wind-swept basketball court at the Modelo Prison as their 
names were called. One by one, they stepped forward to collect certificates 
attesting to their freedom with full rights of citizens. 
</P>
<P>
Then, while loudspeakers blared recorded folk music, ropes separating the 
guardsmen from their families dropped, setting off a scramble of tearful 
reunions. Some of those freed dropped to their knees in prayer. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Shout With Joy' 
</P>
<P>
"Finally, this nightmare is over," said Hazel Maraz Soto, 26, one of the 
youngest prisoners, embracing his mother. She exclaimed, "I want to shout with 
joy that my son has returned!" 
</P>
<P>
Counting 249 prisoners under house arrest or home on furlough, the pardons 
covered 1,894 people imprisoned for service in the army of the Somoza family 
that ruled Nicaragua for 43 years until the Sandinista takeover of July, 1979. 
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine guardsmen remained behind bars, judged by the Sandinistas to be 
guilty of serious war crimes or defiant prison behavior. The pardon did not 
touch any of the 1,400 or more jailed Contra suspects, whose freedom has been 
promised when the Contras lay down their weapons. 
</P>
<P>
The prisoner release, the largest in Nicaragua in two wars spanning more than a 
decade, was the first step taken to comply with President Daniel Ortega's 
commitment under a month-old Central American peace accord, which also promises 
elections in Nicaragua by next Feb. 25. 
</P>
<P>
In return, the region's four other presidents agreed to help draft by mid-May a 
plan for closing the Contra military camps in Honduras, a step that would 
further cripple the idled rebel army. 
</P>
<P>
Ortega has said the Bush Administration is "acting against" the regional accord 
by saying it will seek as much as $50 million in non-military aid from Congress 
to hold the rebels together in Honduras for one more year as a potential threat 
to force Sandinistas to live up to the accord. 
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate his compliance, Ortega brought the secretary general of the 
Organization of American States, Joao Baena Soares, and foreign diplomats to 
the prison ceremony 14 miles east of Managua. 
</P>
<P>
In a later gathering in the capital, Ortega told diplomats and opposition party 
leaders that he will soon send the National Assembly a series of proposed 
changes in the electoral law and the law governing the news media, with the aim 
of assuring open and fair elections. 
</P>
<P>
He said the changes will be based on suggestions offered by 14 opposition 
parties in talks with him in recent weeks, but he gave no details. 
</P>
<P>
Calling the prisoner release "a transcendental act" that shows "the generosity 
of the revolution," Ortega appealed to Washington to limit any new Contra aid 
to the advancement of the regional peace pact -- the rebels' disarmament and 
repatriation to Nicaragua or relocation in third countries. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Rescheduled Date 
</P>
<P>
The prisoner release had been scheduled for Sunday but was moved forward on two 
days' notice when Sandinista officials realized that international attention 
would be distracted by Sunday's elections in El Salvador. 
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders and some former guardsmen said the government seemed more 
concerned about the public relations impact outside Nicaragua than the needs of 
those freed to feel accepted as useful members of society. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, debate over the pardons did little to heal the wounds of the Sandinista 
uprising that left an estimated 10,000 people dead in 1978 and 1979. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Trepidation Voiced 
</P>
<P>
One guardsman on the pardon list, Ramon Valle Arancibia, was the object of a 
last-ditch citizens' campaign to keep him locked up. A mothers group accused 
the ailing, 59-year-old prisoner of having taking part in a June, 1979, 
massacre in a Managua neighborhood and driving the police bulldozer that 
scooped the bodies into a mass grave. 
</P>
<P>
"If I see that man on the street, I'll stone him, I assure you," declared 
Angela Hernandez de Lorio, 55, whose son died in the incident. Valle was freed 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
As they left prison Friday, most guardsmen claimed to be victims of unjust 
prosecution for guilt by association. Some expressed varying degrees of 
trepidation over returning to a society still tightly ruled by the one-time 
guerrillas who defeated them. 
</P>
<P>
Less than an hour after his release, Gustavo Mendoza, 32, looked nervously over 
his shoulder and said he was afraid that Sandinista agents were following him. 
"There is no security for us," he said. 
</P>
<P>
A more typical outlook was expressed by Rodolfo Salmeron, 28, a former National 
Guard officer from the mining town of Siuna, who said he was glad to be alive. 
</P>
<P>
"This is historic," he said. "I think it's hard to find this kind of pardon in 
other countries. I never thought I would get out because first they told us 
that all the guards were going to die. But God never abandoned us, and now 
we're free. Since I never did nothing to anybody, I don't feel the slightest 
fear of going home." 
</P>
<P>
In random interviews with 20 freed guardsmen, eight said they might leave 
Nicaragua because they feel uncomfortable under Sandinista rule or want better 
job opportunities. All but one said they were interested in moving to the 
United States. The U.S. Embassy said there is no special consideration for 
freed guardsmen in its strict immigration rules, although many guardsmen who 
escaped before the Sandinista take-over or were freed later now live in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
The latest batch of guardsmen is being thrown onto a shrinking job market amid 
a severe economic crisis and sharp cutbacks in public spending. Many said they 
were worried more about finding work than about avoiding reprisals. 
</P>
<P>
"I think about leaving, but if they give me a chance to work, I would rather 
stay," said Juan de Dios Herrera, 33, who was trained in prison as a carpenter. 
"I would feel much better with a place in the new society." 
</P>
<P>
The newly freed prisoners will have several sources of assistance. 
</P>
<P>
Mario Arevalo, an official at the Modelo Prison, said 220 of them will continue 
working there, as they did as prisoners, in such jobs as making boots for the 
Sandinista army, repairing government vehicles and building public housing. 
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross gave every freed prisoner a modest wardrobe to go 
home in -- the first civilian clothes many had worn in a decade. It also 
arranged their bus transport home, temporary lodging for about 40 guardsmen 
with no known relatives in Nicaragua and food deliveries for four months. 
</P>
<P>
The Church of God, a Pentecostal sect active inside the prison, will offer 
former guardsmen job placement in rural cooperatives, according to the Rev. 
Pedro Pablo Castillo, a former National Guard lieutenant colonel who left the 
jail in a 1985 pardon. Seven inmates who left Friday will work for the church 
as pastors, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Former Nicaraguan national guardsmen greet families after release from 
prison near Managua. Reuters 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
