<HEADLINE>
<P>
'WILL KILL RUSHDIE,' 50,000 CHANT AT BANGLADESH RALLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DHAKA, Bangladesh 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 50,000 Muslims left mosques and marched throughout the capital Friday 
before gathering at the government's headquarters to demand the death of author 
Salman Rushdie. 
</P>
<P>
Marchers chanted "We will kill Rushdie!" and gathered near the Secretariat, the 
headquarters of the government. 
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, about 3,000 Muslim fundamentalists in Sudan, some shouting "Down, 
down with Britain!" demanded that Sudan break relations with the British 
government, which has defended publication of Rushdie's book "The Satanic 
Verses." 
</P>
<P>
Many Muslims find the book blasphemous because of its depiction of the Prophet 
Mohammed. 
</P>
<P>
Several countries, including Bangladesh and Malaysia, have banned the book, and 
Iran has offered $5.2 million to any Muslim who kills Rushdie, an Indian-born 
Briton of Muslim upbringing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
