<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAWRENCE BERKELEY LAB GETS NEW CHIEF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles Vernon Shank was named Friday to become the new director of the 
Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, the energy and life science research center run 
by the University of California for the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
Shank, 45, now heads an AT&amp;T Bell electronics lab in New Jersey. He will 
take over Lawrence Berkeley in September, succeeding David A. Shirley, who is 
resigning after nine years as director. 
</P>
<P>
Shank earned his bachelor's, master's and Ph. D. degrees from UC Berkeley, 
where Lawrence Berkeley is located. He is an expert in the field of 
spectroscopy of ultra-fast events, the study of processes that take place in 
femtoseconds -- a millionth of a billionth of a second. 
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Berkeley has a staff of more than 3,000 and an annual budget of $220 
million from the U.S. Department of Energy. Unlike the other two labs that UC 
runs for the federal government, Lawrence Berkeley does not do work on nuclear 
weapons, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
SHANK, CHARLES VERNON; LAWRENCE BERKELEY LABORATORY; SCIENTISTS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
