The suspects had first sprayed the house with gunfire before tossing the fire 
bomb, Sgt. Ed Wilson said. A resulting fire caused about $29,000 in damage to 
the house, City Fire spokesman Jim Wells said. 
</P>
<P>
No arrests were made, and the exact motivation in the attack was not known. 
</P>
