<P>
EXPLOSIONS -- GREECE; INDUSTRIAL ACCIDENTS -- GREECE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031889-0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 32504 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 18, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 6; Column 5; Advance Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1000 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICANS SPOKE THEIR MINDS IN 4-DAY 'SUMMIT' AT THE VATICAN; 
</P>
<P>
LACK OF CLOUT IN VATICAN PUTS U.S. CHURCH AT A DISADVANTAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM MONTALBANO, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
VATICAN CITY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pope John Paul II excused himself briefly from a meeting last week with 
American archbishops to accept the credentials of the new Ethiopian ambassador 
to the Holy See, and to deliver a 3,000-word speech of encouragement to six 
visiting Chilean bishops. 
</P>
<P>
During John Paul's four days with the Americans, the gigantic institution he 
heads announced a major economic reform package and proclaimed a breakthrough 
for religious freedom in Lithuania. As the American bishops headed home, the 
Pope met with 7,000 relatives of Italian missionaries and visited a Roman 
parish. While the returning American prelates prepared for a press conference 
in Washington, he was receiving bishops from Burkina Faso and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
As the papal focus shifts away from the extraordinary meeting with American 
church leaders, it is left to the Vatican bureaucracy to follow up on the 
issues. Veteran Vatican observers say that over the next few months the 
church's Curia, or administrative arm, will seek to accentuate trends already 
under way to assert greater central authority over the maverick Americans. 
</P>
<P>
Some Curia moves will be apparent and others unseen, the observers believe, but 
all will come in the context of the way the Vatican views the 
independent-minded American church. 
</P>
<P>
As seen by the European-dominated Curia, the church in the United States is 
both wealthy and important -- often lamentably so -- as an international trend 
setter. It is, to be sure, large, with 53 million members. But it is also 
small: It amounts to only 6% of the world's Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
In asserting its positions against Vatican traditions of patient jockeying and 
unwavering respect for hierarchical authority, the observers say, the American 
church will be at a disadvantage because of its disproportionately weak clout 
at the Vatican. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Little Power 
</P>
<P>
One ailing American cardinal heads the Vatican equivalent of a ministry. Three 
American bishops direct lesser dependencies, but the most powerful among them, 
the head of the Vatican banks, is being ousted. 
</P>
<P>
The scarcity of Americans within the Curia to translate the peculiarities of 
their outspoken countrymen to the glacial Vatican bureaucracy contributes to 
the mutual cultural incomprehension that was the hallmark of the summit, the 
observers believe. 
</P>
<P>
"America is a 'marketplace society' where ideas have to sell themselves on an 
intrinsic merit. That this would conflict at times with the hierarchical nature 
of the church is not surprising," noted St. Louis Archbishop John L. May, 
president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops. 
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath, issues that triggered brotherly differences of opinion at the 
meeting will likely be the focus of Vatican housekeeping initiatives, the 
observers believe. The sources, who requested anonymity, expect the Vatican to 
seek: 
</P>
<P>
* A more rigorous selection of American bishops to assure support for basic 
doctrines such as the Vatican ban on contraception. The Vatican believes that 
some of the current bishops may be better administrators than pastors. It is 
also concerned about what it considers the theological inadequacy of some of 
them. Although cardinals and bishops are expected to have advanced degrees in 
some theological sciences, many American prelates lack them. Theological 
expertise will weigh more heavily in a selection of future bishops and 
cardinals, the Vatican observers believe. 
</P>
<P>
* A tighter rein on theologians to ensure orthodoxy. Vatican critics blame 
iconoclastic Catholic theologians unchecked by their bishops for divisive 
crosscurrents within the American church. The Vatican has made clear that it 
will not tolerate theological dissent on central issues and expects the bishops 
to correct theological aberrations. In recent years, the Vatican believes, some 
American bishops have virtually ceded teaching authority to their theologians. 
The Vatican wants that stopped. The bishop, above all, says the Pope, must 
himself be a teacher and must know what he is talking about. 
</P>
<P>
* Better theological and philosophical preparation in American seminaries. 
There is no controversy on this point: Americans and Curia cardinals agree with 
professors at church universities here and in the United States that American 
seminarians are generally far behind their European peers in philosophical 
preparation. 
</P>
<P>
* A slowdown in the granting of marriage annulments. American marriage 
tribunals grant about 75% of the annulments worldwide, a figure that sticks in 
the craw of a Curia foursquare behind the indissolubility of marriage. The 
American bishops vigorously defended their tribunals at the summit but in the 
process invited greater Vatican inspection of their operations. 
</P>
<P>
If he is distressed by some of what he finds in the American church, and by the 
materialistic society in which it preaches, there is also a lot that John Paul 
admires about the dynamism of American Catholicism. 
</P>
<P>
Still, it is but one church among many churches in a global constituency of 850 
million Catholics. And, as Vatican loyalists are quick to note, John Paul has 
equal responsibility for all of the churches, and all of the people. Indeed, 
one of the most challenging parts of the Pope's job is that he must teach 
different things to different peoples with equal authority. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Unyielding Preacher 
</P>
<P>
For some Americans and Europeans, John Paul may seem principally a stern 
disciplinarian, a moralist supreme and an unyielding preacher of unpopular 
doctrines. Simultaneously, though, he is an outspoken crusader, the poor man's 
friend who demands decent living standards for African peasants, social justice 
for Brazilian slum dwellers, with freedom of worship for Lithuanian 
shipbuilders, and an end to racism everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
That this Polish Pope of all the Catholics has reservations about some 
practices of the American church, so rich, so free, is more predictable than 
exceptional; so, too, that the bishop of Rome and the heir of St. Peter will 
strive relentlessly to put his house in the order he prescribes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Archibisops, from left, Thomas Kelly of Louisville, John L. May of St. 
Louis and John Quinn of San Francisco hold news conference in Washington after 
returning from Rome meeting with the Pope. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
