<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHORALE'S ROBERT JONES TO LEAVE POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CARIAGA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Robert Willoughby Jones, executive director of the Los Angeles Master Chorale, 
confirmed Friday that he is leaving his post when his contract expires June 30. 
</P>
<P>
"Because of differences in management and musical philosophy, I will be leaving 
the Los Angeles Master Chorale by mutual agreement," Jones said in a prepared 
statement. He has been chief administrator at the Master Chorale since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
Abbott Brown, president of the L.A. Master Chorale Assn., said Jones' departure 
was the result of "a number of different points of view concerning the 
direction of the chorale, which we have been discussing in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at long-range planning consistent with the long-range plans of 
the Music Center, at alternative directions for the chorale, and also at our 
organization's overall structure," Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
He said that the chorale was "in sound financial condition." 
</P>
<P>
"We have had a good financial year," he said. "We are going to conclude the 
season on budget, or even better." 
</P>
<P>
John Currie, the organization's music director since 1986 -- Jones was 
instrumental in bringing the conductor here from Scotland -- was not available 
for comment. DANIEL CARIAGA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
